.TH NET-SCAN 1 "2026-04-29" "net-mgr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
net-scan \- list known hosts on the local network
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B net-scan
.RB [ \-\-quick ]
.RB [ \-\-discover ]
.RB [ \-\-listen
.IR HOST:PORT ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-scan
prints the inventory of known hosts: MAC, IPs, vendor, hostname, and observed
ports. It snapshots the
.B interfaces
and
.B addresses
tables from the daemon \(em it does not actively scan. To trigger an active
sweep first, use
.BR \-\-discover .
This tool replaces the legacy
.IR /usr/local/bin/scan-network .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-quick
Default mode. Snapshot the database and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-discover
Fire an nmap sweep
.RB ( TRIGGER
discover) and wait for it to finish before snapshotting.
.TP
\fB\-\-listen\fR \fIHOST:PORT\fR
Override the manager address. Default 127.0.0.1:7531 or
.BR $NET_MGR_LISTEN .
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Show what's on the network right now:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-scan
.fi
.RE
.PP
Re-sweep and then list (slower; blocks until nmap finishes):
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-scan --discover
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR net-discover (1),
.BR net-show (1),
.BR net-report (1),
.BR net-mgr (7)
